<TITLE> President pins progress on IT </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 12 (bdnews24.com) - President Zillur Rahman, chancellor of Dhaka University, called upon graduating students Saturday to be fully involved with the advancement of information technology. "We will have to reach people the achievement of science and technology. Concerted efforts by the concerned ones including the educational institutions will make the implementation possible," Rahman said in his address to the 45th Convocation of Dhaka University. He said: "We will have to proceed towards the way of development in the competitive world. "We need to be involved fully with the progress of information technology." The 45th convocation, the largest in its history, took off in high spirit Saturday with 9,000 graduates and post graduates celebrating their degrees. The main programme was held from midday at the university's central sports ground. The university conferred honorary degrees on three noted academics  Nobel prize-winning chemist Prof Yuan T Lee, inventor of the Sono arsenic filter Abul Hussam and Indian historian Prof Ranajit Guha. Lee received his honorary degree in person. Hussam, a former DU student, and Guha were not present at the ceremony. Among those receiving degree certificates 4,203 were first-time graduates, 1,328 were post graduates and 58 MPhil holders and 58 PhD holders. The university has said this is the largest convocation in terms of number of graduates and guests. Dhaka University was established in 1921. Its first convocation was held in 1923. Earlier, four convocations have been held since Bangladesh's independence in 1999, 2000 and 2004. The 44th convocation was held in 2008. bdn
